Primitive Data Types 

Apex primitives are Integer, Long, Double, Decimal, Boolean, String, Id, Blob, Date, Datetime, and Time. The numeric ones are worth distinguishing:

Integer — 32-bit signed (~±2.1 billion). Long — 64-bit, for anything bigger.
Decimal — arbitrary fixed precision, the correct choice for currency and anything where rounding matters. All currency/number fields from records come back as Decimal.
Double — 64-bit floating point; fine for scientific math, wrong for money.

The single biggest difference from Java: every Apex variable can be null, including Integer and Boolean. 
There's no unboxed primitive. An unassigned Integer i; is null, not 0. This matters constantly for null handling (below).

Also watch integer division — 5 / 2 is 2, not 2.5. Cast a operand first: 5 / (Decimal)2 or 5.0 / 2.
apexInteger count;              // null, not 0
Decimal price = 19.99;
Boolean isActive;          // null, not false
Id recordId = '001xx000003DGb2AAG';



Collections
List — ordered, indexed, allows duplicates. Your default collection. sObject[] array syntax is interchangeable with List<sObject>.
apexList<String> names = new List<String>{'a', 'b', 'a'};
String[] alsoList = new String[]{'x', 'y'};  // same thing
names.add('c');
String first = names[0];

Set — unordered, unique elements, no index access. Great for deduping and for membership checks (mySet.contains(x)), and for gathering Ids to feed into a SOQL WHERE Id IN :mySet.
apexSet<Id> accountIds = new Set<Id>();
for (Contact c : contacts) accountIds.add(c.AccountId);  // auto-dedupes


Map — key/value, unique keys. The idiomatic Apex pattern is bulkifying with maps to avoid queries in loops. 
A very common shortcut: passing a SOQL query straight into a Map<Id, sObject> constructor auto-keys by record Id.
apexMap<Id, Account> accById = new Map<Id, Account>(
    [SELECT Id, Name FROM Account WHERE Id IN :accountIds]
);
Account a = accById.get(someId);   // returns null if key absent
Note map.get(missingKey) returns null rather than throwing, whereas list[badIndex] throws ListException.


TYPE CASTING 

Widening is implicit (Integer → Long → Double, Integer → Decimal). Narrowing and sObject downcasting need explicit casts:
apexObject o = 'hello';
String s = (String) o;

SObject so = [SELECT Id, Name FROM Account LIMIT 1];
Account acc = (Account) so;   // downcast generic sObject
Keep two mechanisms distinct:

Casting (Integer) someObject — reinterprets an existing reference; throws TypeException if the runtime type doesn't match.
Parsing/conversion Integer.valueOf('42'), String.valueOf(someDecimal), Decimal.valueOf('3.14') — actually converts between representations. Integer.valueOf('abc') throws, so validate first.

Use instanceof before a risky downcast:
apexif (o instanceof Account) {
    Account a = (Account) o;
}

Null handling

Because everything can be null, null-safety is where most runtime NullPointerExceptions come from. Three modern operators help a lot:
Safe navigation ?. (API 51.0+) short-circuits to null instead of throwing:
apexString city = contact?.Account?.BillingCity;   // null if contact or Account is null
Integer n = myList?.size();                     // null if myList is null
Null coalescing ?? (API 59.0+) supplies a fallback:
apexInteger qty = record.Quantity__c ?? 0;
String label = input ?? 'default';
For strings, prefer the built-in checks over manual null comparisons, since they handle null and empty/whitespace in one call:
apexString.isBlank(s)    // true if null, '', or only whitespace
String.isEmpty(s)    // true if null or '' (whitespace counts as non-empty)
String.isNotBlank(s)
One more distinction that bites people: a null collection and an empty collection aren't the same. Iterating a null list throws; iterating an empty one is a no-op. 
If a variable might be null, either initialize it up front (new List<...>()) or guard with ?./a null check before looping.
