What is Apex?

Apex is Salesforce's proprietary, cloud-hosted programming language. 
It's strongly typed and object-oriented, with a Java-like syntax, and it runs entirely on Salesforce servers (you can't run it locally — it executes on the Lightning Platform). 
Its whole reason for existing is to let you add custom business logic to Salesforce: things that fire when records are saved (triggers), 
custom REST endpoints, batch jobs, scheduled jobs, and the server-side controllers behind Lightning/Visualforce UIs.
The defining trait is that it's database-integrated and multi-tenant-governed. 
SOQL and DML are first-class parts of the language — you write [SELECT Id FROM Account] or insert acc; directly, no ORM, no connection strings. 
And because thousands of customers share the same infrastructure, Salesforce enforces governor limits: hard caps per transaction (e.g. 100 SOQL queries, 150 DML statements, 6 MB heap, 10-second CPU). 
Blow a limit and the transaction throws and rolls back. This single fact shapes almost every idiom in the language.


Difference between Apex and Java 

Here's that comparison in paragraph form:
Apex and Java differ in where they run before anything else: Apex executes exclusively on Salesforce's servers, while Java runs anywhere a JVM is available. 
They also handle case differently — Apex is case-insensitive (so Integer COUNT and integer count are the same variable), whereas Java is strictly case-sensitive.
Primitives behave differently too. 
In Apex, every primitive is nullable, so an unassigned Integer is null rather than 0. Java's unboxed primitives, by contrast, can never be null. Database access is another key divide: 
Apex builds SOQL and DML directly into the language syntax, so you can write a query or an insert statement natively, 
while Java relies on external JDBC drivers or ORM libraries to talk to a database.
Resource constraints diverge sharply as well. 
Apex enforces governor limits — hard caps on things like queries, DML statements, and CPU time per transaction — because it runs in a shared, multi-tenant environment. 
Java has no such platform-imposed ceiling; it's bounded only by the hardware and JVM configuration it runs on. Concurrency follows a similar pattern: Apex has no thread model and no Runnable-style constructs, 
with asynchronous work instead handled through platform-specific features like batch or queueable jobs, whereas Java offers a full, general-purpose threading model.

List vs. Set vs. Map
Here's the decision in one line each, then the reasoning:
Use a List when order matters or duplicates are allowed — which is most of the time. Query results come back as Lists, DML operates on Lists (insert myList;), and anything you iterate in sequence is a List. It's your default.
Use a Set when you need uniqueness or fast membership tests. The classic case is gathering foreign keys before a query: loop over contacts, add() each AccountId to a Set<Id> (duplicates collapse automatically), then WHERE AccountId IN :accountIdSet. 
Also reach for it whenever you'd otherwise write "have I seen this before?" logic — mySet.contains(x) is the tool.
Use a Map when you need to look something up by a key. This is the heart of bulkification. 
You have records in one context and need the related record for each without querying in a loop, so you build a Map<Id, SomeObject> once and do O(1) .get(id) lookups inside the loop. 
The Map<Id, sObject> constructor that auto-keys a query by record Id exists precisely because this pattern is so common.

A quick way to choose:

Do I just need to hold things in order / pass them to DML? → List
Do I need "unique values" or "is X in here?" → Set
Do I need "given X, find its Y"? → Map

They compose constantly in real triggers: iterate a List of incoming records, collect parent Ids into a Set, query using that Set, load results into a Map, then iterate the original List again doing Map lookups. 
That four-line dance is probably 80% of what maps and sets get used for in Apex.
